; ─── NEEDS-ALFRED LIST (with proposed defaults) ──────────────────────

(needs-alfred
  :item-1 (
    :question "Should `hash-ref` (Sakura-substrate corpus alias) be promoted to CORE alongside `hash-table-ref`?"
    :context "Priya's 2026-07-18 audit found `hash-ref` corpus-attested with count 636 in Sakura substrate. Both dialects now install it as a CORE alias for hash-table-ref."
    :proposed-default "YES — landed as CORE alias in both dialects. Rationale: dialect compatibility + corpus stability during training. Cost is one extra name in the registry."
    :reversible "YES — remove one def() call and one meta entry to demote.")

  :item-2 (
    :question "Should promise?/make-promise/force use continuation-based `raise-continuable`?"
    :context "R7RS §6.11 distinguishes raise (non-continuable) from raise-continuable (continuable). Motoi interpreter has no first-class continuations, so raise-continuable maps to raise in the current impl."
    :proposed-default "MAP TO raise (current). Rationale: full continuation support is a large engine change; Scheme programs that need continuable exceptions can layer their own retry. Ship the R7RS name so R7RS code compiles; document the caveat."
    :reversible "YES — if continuations are added later, retarget raise-continuable to the new machinery.")

  :item-3 (
    :question "Should vectors be a distinct type from lists (R7RS §6.8) or continue as JS-array-aliased (current)?"
    :context "R7RS spec: vectors are distinct — list? on a vector is #f, vector? on a list is #f. Motoi conflates them (both are JS arrays; list? and vector? both return #t on any array). This is a doctrine-level choice."
    :proposed-default "KEEP CONFLATION (current) — Motoi has always represented vectors as JS arrays; splitting them requires reworking every list-taking primitive to distinguish. The R7RS names (vector, make-vector, vector-length, vector-map, vector-for-each, vector-set!, vector-fill!, vector-copy, vector->list, list->vector) all work correctly on the same array representation. If a downstream cart depends on the distinction, we can add a tagged wrapper later without breaking existing code."
    :reversible "PARTIAL — a tagged Vector class could be introduced later; existing code that treats arrays as vectors would need migration."))

; ─── PHASE 1: COVERAGE MATRIX ────────────────────────────────────────

(coverage-matrix
  :table-a-r7rs-small (
